Yes ‚Äî mail has MANY options, not just to and subject.
Online tests love this question because most people only know those two.

I‚Äôll give you everything you need, clearly categorized and easy to remember.

üîë mail METHOD ‚Äî FULL PICTURE

Basic syntax:

mail(options = {})


options is a hash.

1Ô∏è‚É£ MOST COMMONLY USED OPTIONS (MUST KNOW)
mail(
  to: "user@example.com",
  subject: "Welcome"
)

Option	Meaning
to	Recipient
subject	Email subject
2Ô∏è‚É£ VERY COMMON (INTERVIEW FAVORITES)
mail(
  to: user.email,
  from: "support@app.com",
  cc: "manager@app.com",
  bcc: "audit@app.com",
  reply_to: "help@app.com",
  subject: "Order Confirmed"
)

Option	Meaning
from	Sender address
cc	Carbon copy
bcc	Blind carbon copy
reply_to	Reply-to address
3Ô∏è‚É£ MULTIPLE RECIPIENTS (COMMON MCQ)
mail(
  to: ["a@test.com", "b@test.com"],
  cc: ["c@test.com"]
)


‚úî Accepts string or array

4Ô∏è‚É£ HEADERS (RARE BUT IMPRESSIVE)
mail(
  to: user.email,
  subject: "Test",
  headers: {
    "X-Custom-Header" => "Value"
  }
)

5Ô∏è‚É£ CONTENT TYPE / FORMAT
mail(
  to: user.email,
  subject: "Hello",
  content_type: "text/html"
)


Usually not needed because Rails infers from views.

6Ô∏è‚É£ ATTACHMENTS (VERY IMPORTANT)
attachments["invoice.pdf"] = File.read("invoice.pdf")

mail(
  to: user.email,
  subject: "Invoice"
)


üìå Attachments are set before calling mail

7Ô∏è‚É£ TEMPLATE OVERRIDES (TRICK QUESTION)
mail(
  to: user.email,
  subject: "Welcome",
  template_name: "custom_template"
)


Looks for:

custom_template.html.erb

8Ô∏è‚É£ TEMPLATE PATH (RARE)
mail(
  to: user.email,
  subject: "Hello",
  template_path: "shared/mailer"
)

9Ô∏è‚É£ DEFAULT OPTIONS (CLEAN CODE)
class UserMailer < ApplicationMailer
  default from: "no-reply@app.com"

  def welcome_email(user)
    @user = user
    mail(to: user.email, subject: "Welcome")
  end
end

