template_name

###############  template_path vs template_name

1Ô∏è‚É£ template_name

What it does:

Lets you override which view file is used for the email.

Only changes the filename, not the folder.

Example:

# Mailer method
def welcome_email(user)
  @user = user
  mail(
    to: user.email,
    subject: "Welcome",
    template_name: "special_welcome"
  )
end


Rails will look for:

app/views/user_mailer/special_welcome.html.erb
app/views/user_mailer/special_welcome.text.erb


‚úÖ Folder stays the same: user_mailer
‚úÖ Only the file name changes

2Ô∏è‚É£ template_path

What it does:

Lets you override the folder path where Rails looks for the view.

Useful if you want to reuse a shared template across multiple mailers.

Example:

def order_email(user)
  @user = user
  @order = order
  mail(
    to: user.email,
    subject: "Order Confirmed",
    template_path: "shared/mailer",
    template_name: "order_notification"
  )
end


Rails will look for:

app/views/shared/mailer/order_notification.html.erb
app/views/shared/mailer/order_notification.text.erb


‚úÖ Folder is overridden: shared/mailer
‚úÖ File name is overridden: order_notification

